"title": "7336: circumcision, spiritual",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "7336",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>On its own, the physical sign of circumcision is no guarantee of finding favour in the sight of God. It was intended to be the outward sign of inward consecration and should be accompanied by repentance, faith and obedience. Paul stresses that circumcision confers no special privileges upon individuals; it is faith in God, rather than any outward sign, that ensures that believers stand in a right relationship to God.</p>\n<h2>Physical circumcision has no value without the obedience of the heart</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut30:6\">DEU 30:6</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut10:14-Deut10:16\">DEU 10:14–10:16</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer4:4\">JER 4:4</a><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom2:28-Rom2:29\">ROM 2:28–2:29</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom2:25-Rom2:27\">ROM 2:25–2:27</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor7:19\">1CO 7:19</a></p>\n<h2>Circumcision and faith</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal5:6\">GAL 5:6</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom3:30\">ROM 3:30</a></p>\n<h3>Abraham's righteousness depended on his faith, not on the covenant of circumcision</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal3:6\">GAL 3:6</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen15:6\">GEN 15:6</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom4:9-Rom4:12\">ROM 4:9–4:12</a></p>\n<h3>Paul values the law as part of God's plan</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom3:1-Rom3:2\">ROM 3:1–3:2</a></p>\n<h2>The sharp debate about circumcision for Christians</h2>\n<h3>The Council of Jerusalem</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts15:1-Acts15:19\">ACT 15:1–15:19</a></p>\n<h3>Jewish Christians in Jerusalem criticise Peter for accepting hospitality from Cornelius and his (uncircumcised) friends</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts11:1-Acts11:3\">ACT 11:1–11:3</a></p>\n<h3>God's acceptance of uncircumcised Gentiles is clear from the outpouring of the Holy Spirit upon them</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts10:44-Acts10:46\">ACT 10:44–10:46</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts10:34\">ACT 10:34</a></p>\n<h3>Peter's misgivings about Gentile believers and the law</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal2:11-Gal2:16\">GAL 2:11–2:16</a> <em>the dispute between Paul and Peter</em></p>\n<h2>Imposing circumcision upon Gentile Christians denies the freedom of the gospel</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal5:1-Gal5:6\">GAL 5:1–5:6</a></strong> <em>To insist on circumcision is to nullify the work of Jesus Christ on the cross.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal2:3-Gal2:5\">GAL 2:3–2:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal3:14\">GAL 3:14</a></p>\n<h2>``Judaisers'' should be resisted</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal5:7-Gal5:12\">GAL 5:7–5:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal6:12-Gal6:13\">GAL 6:12–6:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal6:15\">GAL 6:15</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Phil3:2-Phil3:3\">PHP 3:2–3:3</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Titus1:10-Titus1:11\">TIT 1:10–1:11</a></p>\n<h3>To be ``in Christ'' is to be spiritually circumcised</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Col2:11-Col2:12\">COL 2:11–2:12</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Col3:11\">COL 3:11</a></p>\n<h2>Paul's confidence in Jesus Christ</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Phil3:4-Phil3:9\">PHP 3:4–3:9</a></p>\n<h2>The relationship between baptism and circumcision in the NT</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Col2:11-Col2:13\">COL 2:11–2:13</a> <em>Both circumcision and baptism may each be described as a “seal”. Baptism signifies entry into the new covenant in the same way that circumcision marked initiation into the old</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom4:11\">ROM 4:11</a> <em>Abraham the father of all believers</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor1:21-2Cor1:22\">2CO 1:21–1:22</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Eph1:13\">EPH 1:13</a></p>",
